soc.message

Class SOCGamesWithOptions

  • java.lang.Object
    • soc.message.SOCMessage
      • soc.message.SOCMessageTemplateMs
        • soc.message.SOCGamesWithOptions
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, SOCMessageMulti

    public class SOCGamesWithOptions
extends SOCMessageTemplateMs
    List of all games currently on the server, including their game options. Sent to each connecting client which can understand game options (1.1.07 and newer).

    Robot clients don't need to know about or handle this message type, because they don't create games.

    Introduced in 1.1.07; check client version against SOCNewGameWithOptions.VERSION_FOR_NEWGAMEWITHOPTIONS. Older servers sent SOCGames instead.

    Since:
    1.1.07
    Author:
    Jeremy D Monin <jeremy@nand.net>
    See Also:
    SOCGameMembers, Serialized Form

    • Constructor Detail

      • SOCGamesWithOptions

        public SOCGamesWithOptions(java.util.List<?> gameList,
                           int cliVers)
        Constructor from a set of game names/objects; used at server side.

        Before v2.4.50 this was a static toCmd(..) method.

        Parameters:
        gameList - the list of games, as a mixed-content list of Strings and/or SOCGames; if a client can't join a game, it should be a String prefixed with SOCGames.MARKER_THIS_GAME_UNJOINABLE.
        cliVers - Client version; assumed >= SOCNewGameWithOptions.VERSION_FOR_NEWGAMEWITHOPTIONS. If any game's options need adjustment for an older client, cliVers triggers that.
        Since:
        2.4.50

    • Method Detail

      • createNewGameList

        public SOCGameList createNewGameList(SOCGameOptionSet knownOpts)
        Get the list of games (and option strings). List contains each game's name and option strings sent from server, as packed by SOCGameOption.packOptionsToString(opts, false, false).

        Game names may be marked with the prefix SOCGames.MARKER_THIS_GAME_UNJOINABLE; this will be removed from their names before adding to the returned game list. To see if a game cannot be joined, call SOCGameList.isUnjoinableGame(String).

        The returned list has null knownOpts, so don't call SOCGameList.parseGameOptions(String) on its members.

        Parameters:
        knownOpts - Known Options to use when constructing the returned list
        Returns:
        list of games contained in this message, or an empty SOCGameList
        See Also:
        SOCGameList.parseGameOptions(String)
